## 

:::: {.center}
Consider the problem of generating samples $\{q_1, \dots, q_n\} \sim \pi(q) \propto e^{-U(q)}$


:::: {.columns .small}

::: {.column width="50%"}
::: {.r-stack}
::: {.content-box-solid-lightorange .fragment fragment-index=1 .fade-out}
**Hamiltonian Monte Carlo** 

1. Given state $q$, sample _auxiliary momentum_ $p$[$\sim \mathcal{N}(0, \Sigma)$]{.footnotesize}+br+br
2. For $(q, p) \sim e^{-H(q,\, p)}$ in the joint state-space+br
treat [$H(q, p)$]{.footnotesize} as the **Hamiltonian of a physical system**+br+br
3. Simulate Hamiltonian dynamics for time $T$ using the **Leapfrog Integrator** to propose new state $(q',\  p')$+br+br
4. Accept/Reject the proposed state with probability+br
[$\hspace{4em}\displaystyle\alpha(q', q) = \min\pb{ 1, {e^{-H(q',\  p')}}\Big/ e^{-H(q',\  p')} }$]{.footnotesize .center}
:::

::: {.content-box-solid-lightorange .fragment .fade-in-then-out fragment-index=1}
+br+br
If $\pi(q) \propto e^{-U(q)}$ has multiple modes,+brHMC can get **trapped**+br+br
⚠️ Energy barriers prevent transitions between modes ⚠️
+br+br+br
:::

